== Overview == During the {{ill|Edo period|ja|江戸時代|12=draft}}, the Konpira faith spread widely across Japan through the efforts of maritime traders and merchants as shipborne commerce became more common. Branch shrines were established in many locations. Following the {{ill|Shinbutsu bunri|ja|神仏分離|12=draft}} (separation of Shinto and Buddhism) and the {{ill|Haibutsu kishaku|ja|廃仏毀釈|1=Haibutsu kishaku|12=draft}} (abolition of Buddhism) during the {{ill|Meiji Restoration|ja|明治維新|12=draft}}, the syncretic Konpira Daigongen faith was dismantled. Konpira shrines became Shinto shrines dedicated to Ōmononushi no Kami as their primary deity. There are about 600 shrines nationwide that align with the head shrine, {{ill|Kotohiragū|ja|金刀比羅宮|1=Kotohira-gū|12=draft}}, worshipping Ōmononushi no Kami. Notably, there are still {{ill|Konpira Gongen#Shrines venerating Konpira Daigongen|lt=Shrines venerating Konpira Daigongen|ja|金毘羅権現|12=draft}} that continue to enshrine Konpira Daigongen without changing the main deity. {{main|Kotohiragū|Konpira Gongen}}
